<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910422-0019</DOCNO><DOCID>910422-0019.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Soviet Data Show Unrest   Badly Hurting Economy   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>04/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)LABOR, PERSONNEL ISSUES, TRENDS, MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES (LAB)</NS><RE>SOVIET UNION (UR)</RE><LP>   MOSCOW -- New Soviet data confirm how spreading strikesand unrest are crippling the economy. In the first quarter,gross national product fell 8% from a year earlier,productivity dropped 9% and foreign trade slumped 33%.   &quot;It can be supposed that the universal fall in economicactivity witnessed during the first quarter will continue,&quot;Goskomstat, the state statistics committee, said. Collapsingoil production led to a 45% decline in imports, because theoil industry is the country's main hard-currency earner. Theminers' strikes and disruption of traditional economic linkscaused by separatism in the republics have brought the Sovieteconomy to the verge of collapse.</LP><TEXT>   The Soviet Parliament is to start discussing today acrisis program that includes a moratorium on strikes, a banon protests during working hours and a crackdown on republicsthat have withheld tax collections from the Kremlin.   The quarterly data &quot;bear witness to the extremely complexand contradictory economic situation in the country,&quot;Goskomstat said. &quot;The signs of crisis in the economy spreadto virtually all spheres,&quot; it said, and production ofconsumer goods and food, both in short supply, is falling.</TEXT></DOC>